## How we got there

### Content strategy

We built the strategy around long-tail, low-competition, high-intent keywords. Instead of going after broad terms where Investopedia and NerdWallet already dominate, we targeted specific queries where quality answers did not exist.

- Strategy grounded in the Publication Context and Audience Personas documents
- Organized into 3 foundational content clusters and 3 core verticals (SaaS, professional services, e-commerce)
- All keyword selection prioritized high-intent commercial queries with low difficulty, plus pain-point-driven informational keywords
- Managed through an Airtable-based ContentOS for assignments, tracking, and prioritization

### Content production cadence

- Week 2: 7 articles delivered, 13 in progress
- Weeks 3 through 9: roughly 5 articles per week
- Weeks 10 onward: shifted to 3 long-form articles plus 4 fan-out posts per week

### The fan-out post model

Starting in Week 10, we introduced shorter, targeted posts designed to answer specific sub-queries branching off from a parent article. For example, the parent article "Best No-Credit-Check Business Cards for Startups" spawned four fan-out posts:

- Is it possible to get a business credit card with no credit check?
- What types of business cards don't require a personal guarantee?
- What are the best no-credit-check alternatives?
- Can you get a business credit card using only an EIN?

Early results were mixed. A few of these posts (roughly 3 to 5 out of 10+) were cited by AI engines within 5 days of publication. Not all of them got picked up quickly, and the standard long-form articles aligned to SEO keyword research have performed better overall. We are still experimenting with the fan-out model and need more data before drawing firm conclusions about how it compares to the long-form approach.

### Reactive content

In Week 9, we published a timely piece on Capital One's acquisition of Brex and refreshed the existing Brex alternatives article to reference it. Results:

- The Brex article became one of the most-visited pages on the site (3.2K impressions, consistent AI agent traffic)
- Average Google position for the Brex alternatives article improved from 18.2 to 8.1 after the refresh
- Citation frequency increased noticeably from late January onward

### Editorial quality and iteration

Victoria provided detailed feedback on early article batches. We rolled all of that feedback into the writing guidelines and production artifacts so every article after that was consistent from first draft. Key refinements:

- Tightened voice to match the peer-to-peer credibility standard
- Made sure all statistics had proper sourcing
- Eliminated AI writing patterns
- Maintained industry-specific focus when keywords specified a vertical
- Added a rule to never refer to Ramp as a bank (came out of a legal discussion in Week 11 about the Treasury product)

### Website

