### Backlinks

We pursued backlinks from three sources:

- **Ramp properties:** A direct backlink from Ramp to Cash Flow Desk, executed after Week 6
- **External editorial sites:** monograph.com linking to the common bookkeeping mistakes article
- **YouTube channel:** Adding Cash Flow Desk links to existing and new video descriptions

#### YouTube integration

Starting in Week 7, we identified existing YouTube videos for adding Cash Flow Desk links and proposed new videos based on two criteria: articles already gaining traction and articles that needed a visibility boost. We also recommended updates to the YouTube channel description and customization page to include the website link.

## Issues we encountered and how we fixed them

### Ramp mention calibration

The team needed alignment on how and where Ramp should be mentioned. We established clear guidelines:

- Ramp mentions only in natural-fit topics (expense management, corporate cards, AP automation, vendor payments, spend visibility)
- Not in general accounting education, payroll, or tax content
- Every mention passes an "honesty test" where it feels genuinely helpful rather than promotional

## Key takeaways

### Speed matters for timely content

After refreshing the Brex alternatives article to reference the Capital One acquisition, Google position went from 18.2 to 8.1, and citation frequency increased.

### Fan-out posts show early promise but need more testing

The fan-out model (short, targeted posts answering specific sub-queries) showed some early signs of working, with a few posts getting cited within days of publication. Not all of them got picked up quickly, and the standard long-form articles aligned to SEO keyword research have been the more reliable performers so far. We need to keep experimenting with the content mix before we can say definitively how fan-out posts compare to long-form in terms of citation efficiency.

### Consistent publishing compounds

Domain authority went from 0 to 6 in roughly 10 weeks. Bot traffic grew from near-zero to 3,200+ weekly requests. This came from consistent quality publishing, strategic internal linking, and backlink acquisition.

### AI visibility is a measurable channel

Citation counts ranged from 277 (7-day) to 797 (14-day) at a steady 2% citation rate across the tracking period.

## Why the best results are still ahead

Most of the results in this retro happened at domain authority 0 or 2. We only recently hit 6.

We have two backlinks total: one from Ramp and one from monograph.com.

Domain authority and backlinks are the two biggest levers for search rankings and AI citation rates. As we continue publishing, acquiring more backlinks, and building internal linking depth, domain authority will keep climbing. As that happens:

- Articles will rank higher on Google, which increases the likelihood that AI engines pull from them
- New articles will get indexed faster
- Citation rates should increase beyond the current 2% baseline
- We will be able to compete for broader, higher-volume prompts (like "best expense management software") that we are not yet winning
- Existing articles that are currently ranking on page 1 or 2 will move up

Going from 0 to 6 domain authority in 10 weeks with two backlinks means there is a lot of room to grow as we add more backlinks and continue publishing.

